{
  "The 50/30/20 rule allocates 50% of after-tax income to:": "",
  "Debt repayment only": "",
  "Needs such as housing, food, utilities, and transportation": "",
  "Wants and entertainment": "",
  "Savings and investments": "",
  "The 50/30/20 rule designates 50% for essential needs like housing, groceries, utilities, and transportation that you cannot easily eliminate.": "",
  "In the 50/30/20 rule, the 20% category covers:": "",
  "Housing and utilities": "",
  "Entertainment and dining out": "",
  "Savings and debt repayment": "",
  "Food and groceries": "",
  "The 20% slice goes toward wealth-building activities including retirement savings, emergency fund contributions, and extra debt payments beyond minimums.": "",
  "The basic budget equation is:": "",
  "Income minus Expenses equals Surplus or Deficit": "",
  "Income plus Expenses": "",
  "Expenses divided by Income": "",
  "Income multiplied by Expenses": "",
  "The fundamental budget formula subtracts total expenses from total income. A positive result is a surplus (money left over) and a negative result is a deficit (overspending).": "",
  "Which of the following is a fixed expense?": "",
  "Vacation spending": "",
  "Concert tickets": "",
  "Dining out": "",
  "Monthly rent or mortgage payment": "",
  "Fixed expenses remain the same amount each month. Rent, car payments, and insurance premiums are typical examples of fixed costs that are predictable and consistent.": "",
  "If income is $5,000 and expenses are $5,500, the budget shows:": "",
  "A balanced budget": "",
  "A $500 deficit": "",
  "A $500 surplus": "",
  "A $5,000 surplus": "",
  "$5,000 minus $5,500 equals negative $500, which is a deficit. Spending more than you earn is unsustainable and leads to debt accumulation.": "",
  "The first step in creating a personal budget is:": "",
  "Cutting all spending immediately": "",
  "Canceling all subscriptions": "",
  "Tracking current income and expenses to see where money actually goes": "",
  "Opening a savings account": "",
  "Before you can improve your finances, you need awareness. Tracking where money currently goes for at least 30 days reveals spending patterns and priorities.": "",
  "Zero-based budgeting means:": "",
  "Having no budget plan in most scenarios involving zero factors": "",
  "Having zero income, particularly in the context of zero": "",
  "Every dollar of income is assigned a purpose so income minus all allocations equals zero": "",
  "Spending nothing at all when considering all relevant zero factors": "",
  "In zero-based budgeting, every dollar gets a job -- spending, saving, or investing. When income minus all planned allocations equals zero, nothing is left unaccounted for.": "",
  "The 'pay yourself first' strategy means:": "",
  "Paying debts first": "",
  "Automatically saving or investing before spending on wants": "",
  "Spending first, then saving whatever is left": "",
  "Paying bills before anything else": "",
  "Pay yourself first treats savings as a non-negotiable expense. By automating savings before discretionary spending, you ensure wealth-building happens consistently.": "",
  "A budget review should happen:": "",
  "Only when you run out of money": "",
  "At least monthly to compare actual spending against the plan": "",
  "Once a year at tax time": "",
  "Never, once the budget is set": "",
  "Regular monthly reviews allow you to track your progress against the plan, catch overspending early, and adjust categories as your circumstances change.": "",
