  "What is discretionary spending?": "",
  "Automatic bill payments": "",
  "Spending on non-essential items you choose to buy, such as dining out and entertainment": "",
  "Fixed costs that never change": "",
  "Required expenses like rent and utilities": "",
  "Discretionary spending covers non-essential, optional purchases that you choose to make. This category offers the most flexibility for budget adjustments.": "",
  "What is the envelope system in budgeting?": "",
  "A type of investment account": "",
  "An online banking feature for automatic payments": "",
  "A method of mailing bills to creditors": "",
  "Putting cash in labeled envelopes for each budget category, and stopping spending when an envelope is empty": "",
  "The envelope system is a physical budgeting method where you allocate cash to labeled envelopes for each spending category. When the envelope is empty, spending in that category stops until the next pay period.": "",
  "What is a sinking fund?": "",
  "A failing investment that loses money": "",
  "A checking account with no interest": "",
  "Money set aside regularly for a planned future expense like a vacation or car repair": "",
  "An emergency savings account": "",
  "A sinking fund is a purposeful savings strategy where you set aside small amounts each month toward a known future expense, such as holiday gifts, car maintenance, or an annual insurance premium.": "",
  "What does 'budget surplus' mean?": "",
  "Spending more than you earn": "",
  "Borrowing money to cover expenses": "",
  "Having money left over after all expenses are paid": "",
  "Breaking even with zero remaining": "",
  "A budget surplus occurs when income exceeds expenses. This leftover money can be directed toward savings, investments, or accelerated debt repayment to build wealth.": "",
  "What is a variable expense?": "",
  "A debt payment with a fixed schedule": "",
  "An expense that stays the same every month, like rent": "",
  "An expense that fluctuates from month to month, such as groceries or utilities": "",
  "A one-time annual payment": "",
  "Variable expenses change in amount from month to month. Groceries, utilities, entertainment, and fuel are common examples whose costs fluctuate based on usage and choices.": "",
  "What does 'needs vs. wants' mean in budgeting?": "",
  "Needs are expensive items; wants are cheap items": "",
  "Needs are things you desire; wants are necessities": "",
  "Needs are essential expenses required for survival and basic functioning; wants are optional purchases for enjoyment": "",
  "There is no difference between needs and wants": "",
  "Distinguishing needs from wants is fundamental to budgeting. Needs include shelter, food, and transportation; wants include dining out, entertainment, and luxury upgrades. A basic smartphone is a need; the latest $1,200 model is a want.": "",
  "What is lifestyle creep?": "",
  "A savings strategy that grows over time without accounting for additional influences": "",
  "A method to reduce spending gradually regardless of prevailing conditions in practice": "",
  "The tendency to increase spending as income rises, preventing savings improvement despite earning more": "",
  "A type of budget surplus, especially during periods of significant change": "",
  "Lifestyle creep occurs when spending rises in tandem with income increases. Instead of saving or investing the extra earnings, people upgrade their lifestyle, keeping their savings rate stagnant.": "",
  "What does 'budget deficit' mean?": "",
  "Spending more than you earn, resulting in negative cash flow": "",
  "A balanced budget with zero left over": "",
  "A successful savings plan": "",
  "Having extra money after expenses": "",
  "A budget deficit means expenses exceed income. This shortfall must be covered by savings, credit, or borrowing, which is unsustainable long-term and leads to growing debt.": "",
  "What is the 30% rule for housing?": "",
  "You should save 30% of income for a home down payment": "",
  "You should spend 30% of income on home improvements": "",
  "30% of a mortgage goes to interest": "",
  "Housing costs should not exceed 30% of your gross income": "",
  "The 30% rule is a guideline suggesting that housing costs -- including rent or mortgage, insurance, and property taxes -- should not exceed roughly 30% of gross income to maintain a balanced budget.": "",
  "What is an irregular expense?": "",
  "A monthly bill that stays the same amount without accounting for additional influences": "",
  "A fraudulent charge on your account regardless of prevailing conditions in practice": "",
  "A daily purchase like coffee, even when conditions shift significantly": "",
  "An expense that occurs periodically but not monthly, such as annual car registration or semi-annual insurance": "",
  "Irregular expenses occur on non-monthly cycles -- quarterly, semi-annually, or annually. Examples include car registration, holiday gifts, and insurance premiums. Smart budgeters divide these by the number of months and set aside funds monthly.": "",
  "Marcus earns $5,200/month after taxes. Using the 50/30/20 rule, how much should he allocate to wants, and if his actual wants spending is $1,800/month, how much is he overspending in that category?": "",
